title: Grateful Dead Live at Nassau Veterans Memorial Coliseum on 1990-03-29
description:
Set 1

Jack Straw ->
Bertha 
We Can Run 
Ramble On Rose

The Promised Land  

Set 2

Drums ->

Dark Star ->

reviews.review_text:
Amazing First source actually confirmed as Matrix for this incredible show.  Thanks for the great work on this, the sound is absolutely perfect.  I'll just let all the reviews of the other sources speak to the quality of the performance itself.  Leave it to say that it easily matches the quality of the recording.  Birdsong and Eyes are ones for the ages.  Jerry and Branford obviously had a chemistry that resulted in some of the best interplay you're ever gonna here between two musicians.  Jaw dropping doesn't come close to how good some of this is. 
Don't like the later Dead?  I think you'll like this one.
Fabulous sounding FLAC's Fantastic job, the FLAC's sound really fabulous on a big Linn system; not too sure that my neighbours would agree, though! :)

Mislabeled 2nd Darkstar is really The Wheel.
Still a great show, love the Estimated

All time classic One of the great shows of the Brent era. Branford's contributions are beautiful and elegant. The band clearly rise to the occasion and play a second set for the ages. Haven't listened to this in a very long time and had forgot what an incredible performance this was.Likely the best post 74 Dark Star and the most beautiful Knocking on Heaven's Door you'll ever hear.

I agree Great sound, thanks for the matrix!

Highlights--we all know what they are: Bird Song, Eyes, DARK STAR.

Someone below mentioned the Estimated. Yes, that too. But I'll add that I've never heard Throwing Stones sound so great. And, of course, Lovelight--though I'd rather hear McKernan belt it out any day--this one as good as anyone could ask.Great encore, also.

I believe this is my all time favorite 90's show. Again, thanks for getting it to us as a matrix!

Jack Straw/Bertha Jack Straw is one of my two favorite first set "speed jams" coupled here with another dancing favorite which happens to be the first song I ever heard live, Bertha. Bill and Mickey really shine here as the Dead's backbone.
wow this is great all around, exellent sound, super trippy bird song, right on ! I didnt think i liked the saxaphone with the dead, but this show is awesome ! I really felt it, thanks.

make a joyful noise Man! Listen to the crowd upon hearing the intro to Dark Star!...I'm a Bay Area fan for seeing shows but there is (was) truly nothing like a New York/New Jersey Area Dead show for sheer hyper enthusiasm.
